<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>     In her dreams she was running, and then was a child again in the training hall.  She was on her pallate on the floor.  She heard the others around her.  She heard the heavy boot steps of the warriors.  She screamed as the hand grabbed her and held her aloft by the tunic. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Kiaran sat up in bed with a scream gulping air into her lungs, her heart hammering in her chest.  She waited hoping she heard no running of feet.  She sighed, she should be over those silly dreams by now.  It was probably just her mind working in her sleep.  She had thought she'd given up finding out who she was or where she had come from.  She accepted she had no house, the Harvest had become her family.  She washed, dressed and went to the room and again.  She began to work out in front of the fire.  She lost her mind to the balance of weapons, movement and the training.  As she worked she emptied her mind, slowly wiping all emotion from her.  Her violet eyes turned cold and blank, her fine features lost the softness.  Once again she pushed all but her warrior from her.  She worked until every muscle screamed in protest and her limbs refused to fight.  She pushed until her weapons became to heavy to bear, her breaths were labored and she dripped sweat.  When she could move no longer she fell to her knees before the fire.  Violet eyes stared blankly into the flames.  She finally moved back to her room, washed and fell into bed, she was asleep before her head hit the pillow and long after the first rays of light shown.<br>
<br>
Several nights later, when all the Grange is quiet Kiaran slips back out into the dark of the city.  She has changed her armor for street clothes and tucked her sword out of sight.  She quietly navigates the streets to The Cauldron of Hate.  Her memory serves her well and she finds her old tutor's rooms.  The old warrior looks up from his desk and smiles.  &quot;Come in, Child.  I hear you have a new home.&quot;  Kiaran enters and slides into a chair.  &quot;Aye I have a new home for a moment in the Grange til I am judged.  Then it becomes perment. But I have come on a more personal errand.&quot;  The old warrior nodded.  &quot;What is it Child that you seek?&quot;  Kiaran sighes and whispers &quot;I seek my begining, Sir.  Not that you did not train me well or that I am not grateful for my new home.  But I have visions or dreams that make no sense.&quot;  <br>
<br>
The warrior nodded.  &quot;Then the time has come Child.  But you must choose.  Do you wish to know or can you let it go?&quot;  Kiaran frowned.  &quot;I may not wish to know it all.  Can you tell me how I came to be here.&quot;  The old warrior nodded.  &quot;You were given to me when you were but a babe.  But I had known you long before then.  I had known your father.  Your father was a good man and good fighter, but a warrior he was not.  Your father, Dakkan, was a shadowknight. &quot; Kiaran said &quot;So I am a orphan then?&quot;  The old warrior sighed. &quot;Child before we go any further you need to decide what you want to know.&quot; <br>
<br>
It did not take Kiaran very long to decide that she at least wanted to know.  Several days later she again snuck out at dark to visit the old warrior.  This time he simply handed her a book with worn pages.  <br>
<br>
The following is the begining to her story.<br>
